<sect2 xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" id="gimp-filter-saturation">
  <title>Saturation</title>
  
  <indexterm>
    <primary>Colors</primary>
    <secondary>Saturation</secondary>
  </indexterm>
  <indexterm>
    <primary>Saturation</primary>
  </indexterm>
  
  <para>
    Another way to modify saturation. Clear explanations about chroma and 
    saturation can be found at 
<ulink url="https://ninedegreesbelow.com/photography/changing-saturation-using-lch-chroma.html"/>
  </para>
  <note>
    <para>
      This command does not work on Grayscale images. If the image is Grayscale,
      the menu entry is disabled.
    </para>
  </note>

  <sect3>
    <title>Activating the Command</title>
    <para>
      You can access this command from the main menu through
      <menuchoice>
        <guimenu>Colors</guimenu>
        <guimenuitem>Saturationâ€¦</guimenuitem>
      </menuchoice>.
    </para>
  </sect3>
  
  <sect3>
    <title>Options</title>
    <figure>
      <title>Saturation Options</title>
      <mediaobject>
        <imageobject>
          <imagedata fileref="images/menus/colors/saturation-dialog.png" 
format="PNG"/>
        </imageobject>
      </mediaobject>
    </figure>
    <variablelist>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>Presets</term>
        <term>Blending Options</term>
        <term>Preview</term>
        <term>Merge filter</term>
        <term>Split view</term>
        <listitem>
          <xi:include href="about-common-features.xml"/>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>Scale</term>
        <listitem>
          <para>
            This option gives more or less saturation.
          </para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>Interpolation Color Space</term>
        <listitem>
          <para>
            This option determines in which color space the saturation
            computations are done. You can choose from
            <guilabel>Native</guilabel>, which means the color space of the
            image (default), <guilabel>CIE LAB/Lch</guilabel>, and
            <guilabel>CIE Yuv</guilabel>.
          </para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
    </variablelist>
  </sect3>
  
</sect2>
